&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; But if we use Mediator to decouple the gui controls, we may as
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; well delegate
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; everything to the Mediator and leave the gui stupid. The Mediator can
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; be
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; unit tested just like any other class, and doesn&#39;t need the gui since
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; all
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; communication is done through interfaces.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; That notwithstanding, you still need to test the connection between the
&gt;&gt;&gt; mediator and your GUI. There&#39;s still plenty of room for error there.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I&#39;m trying to understand your concern. I can test that the Mediator
&gt;&gt; send the
&gt;&gt; right message with the right parameters at the right time. The code in
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt; gui (let&#39;s say a Dialog box just to be concrete) that responds to this
&gt;&gt; message is one or two lines of code which IMO, can&#39;t break.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Can you show me in a few lines of code where there is room for error
&gt;&gt; between
&gt;&gt; the Mediator and the gui/dialog/whatever?
